WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.130 --> 00:00:03.690
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.690 --> 00:00:08.820
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA
200-301.

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:12.810
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:12.810 --> 00:00:17.880
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:19.140
of videos.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:20.140
Thanks for your help.

00:00:20.140 --> 00:00:22.630
Let’s get started.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:27.169
In this lab we will examine some network traffic
using packet tracer’s ‘simulation mode’

00:00:27.169 --> 00:00:28.169
feature.

00:00:28.169 --> 00:00:32.619
But first, let’s take a look at the network
diagram.

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:41.390
There are two routers, R1 and R2, two switches,
SW1 and SW2, and one server and one pc.

00:00:41.390 --> 00:00:51.370
The G0/0, G0/1, G0/2 and F0/1 labels indicate
the network interfaces used to connect the

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:53.420
devices.

00:00:53.420 --> 00:01:00.890
G means gigabit ethernet, so these interfaces
operate at a speed of one gigabit per second.

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:09.840
You migth also see it written as Gi, or Gig,
but I usually just use G. F means fastethernet,

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:14.100
so these interfaces operate at 100 megabits
per second.

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:20.600
You might also see it written as Fa, instead
of just F. Now these two series of numbers

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:32.140
here, 192.168.1.0/24, and 10.0.0.0/24, are
the network addresses.

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:35.280
Routers are used to connect different networks.

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:39.700
There are two networks displayed here in this
diagram, the one on the left here includes

00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:47.819
SRV1, PC1, SW1, SW2, and R1’s G0/0 interface.

00:01:47.819 --> 00:01:52.880
They are all in a single network, or subnet,
a term you will learn about soon.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:02:04.469
So, that’s the 192.168.1.0/24 network, and
the .100 for SRV1 means that its IP address

00:02:04.469 --> 00:02:14.830
is 192.168.1.100, and the .1 by R1 means that
its address is 192.168.1.1.

00:02:14.830 --> 00:02:20.500
Wait for the lesson about IP addresses coming
up soon for more information on this topic.

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:27.940
The other network is 10.0.0.0/24, consisting
of R1’s G0/1 interface, and R2’s G0/0

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:28.940
interface.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:40.470
Notice the .1 and .2, so R1 is 10.0.0.1 and
R2 is 10.0.0.2.

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:44.810
Hopefully that helps you understand a little
bit about how to read a network diagram.

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:50.960
Don’t worry if you have no idea how IP addresses
work, or what that /24 next to the network

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:54.850
addresses means, that will all be explained
in a video coming soon.

00:02:54.850 --> 00:02:58.030
So let’s get started on today’s main topic.

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:03.090
I’m going to use packet tracer’s simulation
mode, which you can activate here, in the

00:03:03.090 --> 00:03:04.500
bottom right.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:10.760
Now, I can click through here, and you can
see various network traffic being sent around.

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:14.480
Let’s take a look at some.

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:20.300
At Device SW2 means that SW2 is the one sending
out the data.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.820
It says type, STP.

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:29.200
STP is the spanning-tree protocol, a layer
2 protocol you’ll learn a lot about in this

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.260
course.  Let's click on it, and

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:38.340
notice here the 7 layers of the OSI model,
and STP has information in the bottom two

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:39.340
layers.

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:43.250
Let’s look at the Layer 2 header.

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:48.960
Notice it says Layer 2: IEEE 802.3 header.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:55.020
You might remember that IEEE 802.3 is the
standard number for Ethernet, so this is an

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:57.150
Ethernet Layer 2 header.

00:03:57.150 --> 00:04:00.790
Let’s look at some of the information here.

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:04.930
Down here it shows some information about
the process, and notice here at number

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:10.150
2: the device encapsulates the PDU into an
Ethernet frame.

00:04:10.150 --> 00:04:14.370
There’s the encapsulation process I talked
about in the lecture video.

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:18.440
Let’s take a look at the Layer 1 info.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:24.190
Notice that the information is the two interfaces
that it sends the frame out of.

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:29.420
Information like the physical ports, or interfaces,
on a device are Layer 1 information, because

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:31.590
it is the physical layer.

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:39.750
Now let’s look at another bit of network
traffic, this time AT device R1, and the type

00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:41.870
is OSPF.

00:04:41.870 --> 00:04:49.880
OSPF is a layer 3 protocol, it’s used to
discover the best paths to different networks.

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:53.410
You’ll learn a lot about it, too, in this
course.

00:04:53.410 --> 00:05:02.320
STP only had Layer 2 and Layer 1 information,
but OSPF has Layer 3, Layer 2, and Layer 1

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:03.470
information.

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:09.620
Notice in the Layer 3 header, source IP address,
and destination IP address.

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:14.240
Remember, IP addresses are Layer 3 information.

00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:19.720
Next, to look at some traffic that includes
information all the way up to Layer 7, I will

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:21.660
go on PC1.

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:30.040
Pc1 is using a protocol called DHCP to automatically
receive an IP address.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:37.240
To generate some DHCP traffic, and DHCP is
a layer 7 protocol, I’ll get PC1 to release

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:41.500
its current IP address, and then renew it.

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:46.190
When you click on a PC in packet tracer you’ll
see this screen.

00:05:46.190 --> 00:05:51.230
Click on desktop, then command prompt, to
access the PC’s command prompt, which functions

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:54.050
like a windows command prompt.

00:05:54.050 --> 00:06:02.160
Type ipconfig, and you can see the current
IP address here…...to release the IP address,

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:05.850
type ipconfig /release.

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:09.680
And now you can see already a DHCP message
on PC1.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:14.820
I’ll type the next command to, to renew
the IP address.

00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:17.770
It’s ipconfig /renew.

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:22.060
Now let’s check one of these DHCP messages.

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:27.169
Notice information all the way up to Layer
7, except layers 5 and 6.

00:06:27.169 --> 00:06:34.520
That's because in the TCP/IP model, which
is the model actually in use, Layers 5, 6,

00:06:34.520 --> 00:06:38.760
and 7 are all combined into a single layer
called the application layer, so you’re

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:44.550
not going to see any layer 5 or 6 information,
but you can consider it to be part of the

00:06:44.550 --> 00:06:47.280
layer 7 information.

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:54.919
Then there is layer 4 information, if you click on it, it says
the device encapsulates the PDU into a UDP

00:06:54.919 --> 00:06:59.250
segment, remember the Layer 4 PDU is called
a segment.

00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:03.600
Layer 3, Layer 2, and Layer 1 information
is present as well.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:08.990
Now, if I just press the play button in the
middle, it will slowly play through all of

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:12.650
the different messages being sent through
the network.

00:07:12.650 --> 00:07:20.000
That’s all for this lab, I just wanted to
show you the OSI and TCP/IP models at work

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.229
on a network.

00:07:22.229 --> 00:07:27.669
Your understanding of the functions of these
layers might still be a little unclear, but trust me,

00:07:27.669 --> 00:07:31.360
you’ll understand things better as we start
to actually learn about these different protocols

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:36.790
that operate at each layer.

00:07:36.790 --> 00:07:37.979
Thank you for watching.

00:07:37.979 --> 00:07:39.740
That's all for this video.

